Component Scanning with @Component, @Service, @Repository:

Component scanning is how Spring automatically detects and registers beans in your
application, reducing manual configuration.

@Component: Generic stereotype for any Spring-managed component.
@Service: Specialization of @Component for service layer classes.
@Repository: Specialization of @Component for data access layer (DAO) classes. Also adds
exception translation for database errors.
How it works:

Annotate your classes with these annotations.
Enable component scanning in your configuration (with @SpringBootApplication or @ComponentScan).
Example:

@Component
public class EmailSender { }

@Service
public class UserService { }

@Repository
public class UserRepository { }
Spring Boot enables component scanning by default for the main package and sub-packages.

@ComponentScan is basically what scans and defines what beans are to be there, and it is present
by default in @SpringBootApplication annotation. Which enables it to scan the current package
and all its sub-packages . If you explicitly mention @ComponentScan and mention teh package
inside then that particular package will only be considered for bean scanning . You can also
mention array of packages as bean .